One of the most fun projects I got to work on last year was painting backgrounds for the lovely short, “Hair Love” - which won an academy award last night!  The folks at Six Point Harness gave me the opportunity to work on the backgrounds for this short and I had a ton of fun every step of the way. The story absolutely captured my heart as a father of a daughter with beautifully wild wavy & curly hair and the style of the backgrounds Six Point developed was a thrilling challenge to work in.

I’ve been transitioning to painting more and more backgrounds in the animation industry and it’s been such a breath of fresh air working in different styles with artists from around the world, all aiming at achieving the best quality possible. 
I’ve been neck deep in more of these kinds of projects this year and I’m hungry for more! If you’re looking for background painting, hit me up!

#HairLove #6PointHarnessAnimation #2danimation #Oscars #backgrounds #backgroundpainting #ocs #orlincultureshop #brianedwardmiller #2020 #art #beauty

2019 was a busy year, one that definitely challenged me in a bunch of ways. 
I hit a number of milestones and road bumps along the way. There were times I thought I wouldn’t be able to keep up with the amount of work I had to do and slow periods where I wondered if I’d ever get work again. 
It’s the year I decided to start branching out into animation and so far it’s been one of the most rewarding shifts I’ve made in my career - especially from an artistic perspective. 
Here’s hoping 2020 continues to bring artistic growth and lots of fun jobs. 
Thank you all for following along, encouraging and inspiring me. 
#top9of2019 #art #2019 #ocs #orlincultureshop #brianedwardmiller #illustration #beauty #retro #digitalart #artistofinstagram

Here’s a look at the final cover for Luxembourg’s Merkur Magazine. The topic for this cover was “attracting talent in the workplace” and the article keyed in on how employers were bringing in new talent to fill vital roles in the organization. Quite a challenging topic to illustrate.

It’s hard to believe I’ve been doing covers for this magazine since 2015! They’ve been a genuine pleasure to work with and each of the topics they asked me to illustrate stretched me conceptually and artistically. 
They’re shifting the look of the magazine next year which means I will no longer be illustrating the covers - but we had an awesome run together and I wish them well.

Adventures in Spaaaaaace!

This was one of my favorite space-scapes in the 2019 Fontacular campaign. I absolutely love painting these kinds of pieces because they let me explore lighting, whimsical shape designs, atmosphere, storytelling... all the fun stuff! These pieces also let me explore a level of abstraction with textures that feel spontaneous and are a lot of fun to put down.

For those who are interested in process: I do all my sketches in Procreate on the iPad Pro + Pencil. From there I do my final paintings in Photoshop. I use custom pressure sensitive brushes with a wacom cintiq for most of my texturing - and a few stamp brushes specifically for these space scenes.

Be sure to check out the full writeup on my blog where I post tons of breakdowns of these pieces: http://orlincultureshop.com/blog

This was one of my favorite seascape pieces I created for the 2019 Fontacular campaign. I felt as if I was discovering the composition just as much as the explorer was discovering the waterfalls of the lagoon as he reached the peak of one of the towering hills.

One of the unique features about this campaign was I determined the color palette before drawing much of anything. This meant I could throw down rough sketches and then immediately apply color to really let the atmosphere become a part of the piece from the very beginning. 
Be sure to check out the Fontacular campaign which runs Oct 21-25 of this year: https://bit.ly/2MY5fyV

They’re doing a bunch of giveaways and their font bundles are a ton of fun to work with.

This was one of the first type explorations I did for the 2019 Fontacular campaign for @myfonts and I liked the piece so much, I chose it as the piece to make a poster of. 
I always love when type and illustration work comes together well. Both have so many similarities. In fact, I still remember when I was in school for graphic design and I had the epiphany that type can be thought of in terms of shapes (I wasn’t the brightest student). That shifted my perspective on type from that day forward and I always enjoy integrating it into my work when I’m able. 
Be sure to check out the fo tabular campaign for great deals on their type bundles: https://bit.ly/2MY5fyV

Earlier this year I had the good fortune of illustrating the cover for a book titled In The Red, written by Christopher Swiedler and published by Harper Collins. 
The folks at Harper Collins were great to work with and after I received an advanced copy of Christopher’s awesome book, we spent time bouncing different ideas back and forth to determine our route forward. These kinds of collaborations are a lot of fun and I’m definitely thankful for them!

Big thanks to Christopher Swiedler for writing a great book and Jessie Gang for art direction and design!

I had the great fortune of illustrating these awesome dogs for @devilsbackbonebrewingcompany as part of their “Gold Leaf Adventure Dog Contest”. In this contest, dog owners were invited to submit photos of their canine companions and after online voting, the 5 most popular dogs would be featured on cans and boxes of Gold Leaf Lager. 
Over 6,000 dogs were entered and they had over 70,000 votes!

It was such an honor to be a part of the contest - and made me miss my bulldog even more.

Howdy, folks! I’m back in town after a very restful vacation and have a fun #throwbackthursday piece for ya (which is good since all my current projects are under wraps). This is an alternative color option for a background painting I did for “The Umbrella Factory”, a pitch project done for Naissance.

These were my first attempts at backgrounds / layouts / and visual development years ago and I had a ton of fun working on them. I had to keep everything layered so the animators could utilize parallax animation with the different assets. Lot’s of work but it felt like pure joy!
